[normal]3) Public Purposes:
[normal]The fifth of the BBC's Public Purposes as defined in its Charter and Agreement is that of "Bringing the UK to the world and the world to the UK". The BBC Trust's interpretation of that remit includes a commitment to "build a global understanding on international issues". 
[normal]With regard to the Arab-Israeli conflict, the BBC consistently 
[normal]neglects
[normal] to inform its audiences of the scale of terror threats facing Israeli civilians. It frequently ignores incidents of missile fire at civilian targets and 
[normal]other
[normal] terror attacks against them. It downplays the subject of Palestinian terrorism in general and has erroneously portrayed imprisoned terrorists as 'political prisoners' – see 
[normal]here
[normal] and 
[normal]here
[normal].
[normal]The BBC's 
[normal]representation
[normal] of the subject of the Middle East peace process is frequently 
[normal]indistinguishable
[normal] from that of the Palestinian Authority, with disproportionate – and 
[normal]frequently inaccurate
[normal] - emphasis on factors promoted by the PA as 'obstacles to peace'. At the same time, factors no less relevant to the peace process such as the Hamas/Fatah split, Palestinian terrorism, official PA incitement and glorification of terror and Israeli security 
[normal]concerns are given considerably less coverage, thereby hampering audience understanding of the issue. 
[normal]BBC reporting from the areas controlled by the 
[normal]Palestinian Authority
[normal] and Hamas is notable for its consistent avoidance of issues such as the oppression of minorities, women's rights, government corruption and the lack of press freedom. 
[normal]Remarkable too is the sheer scale of BBC reporting on Israel. Over the past nine months (
[normal]March to November 2013 inclusive
[normal]), Israel has consistently been in the top five Middle East countries receiving the most coverage on the BBC News website, despite the fact that much of the rest of the region continues to be plagued by political and military turmoil. 
[normal]One particularly 
[normal]worrying
[normal] characteristic of the BBC's Middle East reporting has been its tendency to promote unchallenged conspiracy theories and propaganda produced by repressive regimes to worldwide audiences – see examples 
[normal]here
[normal], 
[normal]here
[normal], 
[normal]here
[normal], 
[normal]here
[normal] and 
[normal]here
[normal]. 
[normal]The past year has also seen several cases of the 
[normal]downplaying
[normal] of 
[normal]antisemitism
[normal] both 
[normal]in the UK
[normal] and 
[normal]abroad
[normal] by the BBC and moderation of 
[normal]antisemitic
[normal] comments
[normal] on the BBC's 
[normal]public 
[normal]fora
[normal] has not infrequently proved to be inadequate. The BBC's decision to host a known 
[normal]antisemitic
[normal] Holocaust denier 
[normal]on its Persian service
[normal] is a cause for considerable concern and reinforces the impression that educational work on the subject of 
[normal]antisemitism
[normal] is urgently 
[normal]needed
[normal] at the BBC.  
[normal]How should the BBC be governed, regulated and held accountable beyond 2016?[bold]4) The BBC complaints system:
[normal]BBC Watch receives considerable amounts of correspondence from the general public with regard to the BBC's complaints system. Many of those members of the public are frustrated by the system's labyrinthine nature, the difficulties they experience in navigating it and the often slow response time to complaints. 
[normal]Members of the public also express great dissatisfaction with the fact that the BBC is essentially a self-regulating body and that there is no possibility for impartial adjudication of complaints by an independent body. 
[normal]The material collected on this subject by BBC Watch suggests that many members of the public would like to see the establishment of an independent ombudsman to deal with complaints regarding BBC content and that the current system of self-regulation is unsustainable. 
